          `The <strong>SRAS curve slopes upward</strong> from left to right. The logic is straightforward: when the general price level rises but wages and other input costs haven't caught up yet, firms find it more profitable to produce more. Every extra unit sells at a higher price while costs remain roughly the same, so profit margins widen and output expands. This gap between rising output prices and sticky input costs is the entire reason the SRAS slopes upward.`,
          `Think about what happens at a UK factory when retail prices start climbing. The factory's wage contracts were set months ago, its rent is locked in for the year, and its raw material contracts have fixed delivery prices. Higher selling prices mean <strong>higher profit per unit</strong>, which is a powerful incentive to ramp up production — run extra shifts, call in part-time workers, and push machinery harder. This is exactly why real GDP rises along the SRAS when the price level increases.`,
          `Notice how the SRAS curve gets <strong>steeper as the economy approaches full capacity</strong>. When there's lots of spare capacity (high unemployment, idle factories), firms can expand output easily without much upward pressure on costs. But as the economy nears full employment, additional output becomes increasingly difficult: firms compete for scarce workers, overtime premiums kick in, and less efficient machinery is brought into service. Each extra unit of output now requires a disproportionately larger rise in the price level.`,
          `The assumption of <strong>sticky wages</strong> is what makes the SRAS curve different from the LRAS curve. In the short run, workers can't instantly renegotiate their contracts when prices rise — they're locked into agreements. But over time, workers notice their real wages falling and demand higher nominal wages. Once wages fully adjust, the SRAS story breaks down, which is why we need a separate long-run model.`,
          `A useful way to remember the SRAS shape: it's relatively <strong>flat on the left</strong> (spare capacity — easy to expand), <strong>steeper in the middle</strong> (bottlenecks emerging), and <strong>very steep on the right</strong> (approaching full capacity — extra output is extremely costly). Japan's economy in the early 2010s sat on the flat portion, with deflation and excess capacity, while the UK in late 2022 was on the steep portion, with minimal spare capacity and rising inflation.`
