          `The <strong>Keynesian LRAS curve</strong> looks fundamentally different — it has <strong>three distinct sections</strong> rather than being a single vertical line. This shape reflects Keynes's belief that the economy can settle into equilibrium <em>below</em> full employment for extended periods, especially during deep recessions. The debate between these two LRAS shapes is one of the most important in macroeconomics.`,
          `The <strong>horizontal (flat) section</strong> on the far left represents a <strong>deep recession</strong> with massive spare capacity. Here, firms can increase output by rehiring idle workers and restarting mothballed machinery without any pressure on costs. Real GDP can grow with <strong>virtually no increase in the price level</strong>. The UK during the Great Depression of the 1930s, with unemployment above 20%, sat squarely in this flat region.`,
          `The <strong>upward-sloping middle section</strong> represents the economy approaching capacity. As more resources are employed, <strong>bottlenecks</strong> start appearing: skilled workers become scarce in certain sectors even while unemployment persists elsewhere, popular raw materials run short, and logistics networks become congested. Output can still grow, but now it comes with <strong>rising prices</strong>. Most real-world economies operate in this intermediate zone most of the time.`,
          `The <strong>vertical section</strong> on the far right represents absolute <strong>full capacity</strong> — every worker employed, every machine running, every acre planted. Here, the Keynesian LRAS looks identical to the classical version: no more output is physically possible regardless of the price level. This is the economy's absolute ceiling.`,
          `The crucial policy difference is this: in the Keynesian model, if the economy is stuck on the flat or intermediate section, <strong>demand-side policies can increase real output</strong> without generating much inflation. Government spending or monetary expansion actually works to reduce unemployment and raise GDP. This is exactly what Keynes prescribed during the 1930s Depression — and what governments did on a massive scale during the 2020 COVID-19 recession.`,
          `The Keynesian view challenges the classical assumption that wages are flexible downward. Keynes argued that <strong>nominal wages are sticky downward</strong> — workers resist pay cuts, trade unions fight them, and minimum wage laws prevent them. So when demand falls, instead of wages dropping and the labour market clearing (as the classical model predicts), firms just lay people off. The economy gets stuck with <strong>involuntary unemployment</strong> and output well below potential.`,
          `You don't need to "pick a side" in exams — the best answers acknowledge <strong>both views</strong> and evaluate which is more relevant to the situation described. During the 2008–09 financial crisis with massive spare capacity, the Keynesian model had more practical relevance. During the 2022 inflationary spike with the economy near full employment, the classical model's warnings about demand-side stimulus were more pertinent.`
