          `<strong>Demographic changes</strong> affect LRAS over time. An ageing population — like Japan's, where over 29% of the population is now over 65 — reduces the working-age population and shifts LRAS growth potential leftward unless offset by immigration, automation, or higher participation rates. Younger, growing populations (like India's) provide a <strong>demographic dividend</strong> that shifts LRAS rightward.`,
          `Remember that LRAS shifts represent <strong>changes in the economy's potential output</strong> — its speed limit. This is fundamentally different from an SRAS shift, which represents changes in short-run costs. An SRAS shift might reverse quickly (oil prices spike then fall), but an LRAS shift reflects lasting structural change. When an exam question asks about long-run growth, you're always talking about rightward LRAS shifts.`
