          `<strong>Long-run macroeconomic equilibrium</strong> occurs where <strong>AD, SRAS, and LRAS all intersect</strong> at the same point. In the classical model, this means the economy is producing at its full-employment level of output (Yf) — there's no output gap, and inflation is stable. All three curves pass through the same price level and the same real GDP.`,
          `In this long-run equilibrium, there is <strong>no tendency for wages to change</strong>. Firms are satisfied with their output levels, and workers have no reason to demand higher wages (because prices aren't unexpectedly rising) or accept lower wages. The economy is at the <strong>natural rate of unemployment</strong>, where the only unemployment is frictional and structural — not cyclical.`,
          `The Keynesian perspective adds a complication: long-run equilibrium might occur on the flat or upward-sloping portion of the Keynesian LRAS, meaning the economy can be in equilibrium <em>with</em> significant spare capacity and involuntary unemployment. Keynes's famous observation was that "in the long run, we are all dead" — his point being that waiting for the economy to self-correct to full employment could take unacceptably long, causing enormous human suffering in the meantime.`,
          `In practice, most economies fluctuate around long-run equilibrium rather than sitting at it. The <strong>business cycle</strong> describes these fluctuations — periods where actual GDP is above potential (booms) and below potential (recessions). The goal of macroeconomic policy, broadly, is to keep the economy as close to long-run equilibrium as possible, minimising the severity of these swings.`
